^B@2^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| First the auction. 2@H was a good bid. shows an invitational hand  and pass was fine by ally. Now, what should I do? One bridge maxim that is often right is "if they have a fit, you have a fit."  In this case, Ira has at most 4 hearts, so I know they have a heart fit  and I am pretty sure Ira has clubs. so even though I have a bad hand, I do have length in clubs and shortness in hearts, so 3@C is a nice competitive bid. We either make or are down 1. I am not sure what double by pam should mean nor if she should make a double.  I play the double by pam suggests a penalty double. |
PG| ***** 16 ***** |


AT|
onoway: I play anything below game ( the first double) is takeout.|
PG| ***** 17 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Well, it is not really the first double, ally doubled already. I am not sure I like that approach, particularly on this hand.  I think you can just pass. You already described your hand, 10 or 11 points with hearts, and you have nothing beyond what you said on your first bid.  If you want to bid 3@H, because you have a 5th heart, I guess that would be ok, but I don't see why double should not be penalty oriented there. And, if it were sort of takeoutish, I guess I would assume you have spades and hearts, and if I were ally, I would bid 3@S. The problem hand is when you have 10 points and 4 hearts and 4 spades. If you want to play that as takeoutish, I would think you needed a 4th spade. Now, as to the defense. |
PG| ***** 18 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|^B@2^*Bhondo717:^*N|cp||at| Once Ira does not lead a club, I assume he has the ace. Otherwise I would expect a club lead. Anyway, that is why I discouraged clubs, because I did not have the ace or king, and if Ira has the ace but not the king, I do not want him to lead the suit. Some people who play odd/even play that the even card is suit preference for the other suits. I do not like to play that, I just like to play even discourages. I did make a slight error on defense later in the hand. When I led a spade back, I led the 9, not the 8. I did that automatically, since I had 9 and 8 left, and was leading my remaining count. However, I should realize that Ira is going to ruff the spade, because there is only one spade left between pam and Ira, and if Ira had it, pam would have played the ace on the 2nd spade trick. I should realize pam has another spade, and Ira is out. Therefore, I should lead the 8 of spades left to tell Ira to lead clubs back as the suit preference.|
PG| ***** 19 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|My 9 told Ira to lead the higher suit, diamonds, which he obediently did. As far as Ira originally leading trumps, that could work out well. Someone might be ruffing clubs. And when you have Axx or even Axxx as a trump holding, it is often good to under lead an ace at first particularly Axx. With Axx, partner could easily have 2 trumps. By under leading the ace, if partner gets in, he will have another trump, and can lead it, in which case you play ace and another and draw 3 rounds of trumps.  If you led the ace and another trump first, if partner got in, he is not likely to have a 3rd trump, and you would not be able to draw 3 rounds of trumps, if that is the defense you chose.|
