^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|This hand has some very interesting bidding concepts to it. The first two bids are pretty standard. The question is, what tactic is best for Ira, 3@S or 4@S?  I don't think there is a clear cut answer. However, Ira needs to be consistent. If he chooses to bid 3@S, then I think he should pass the 4@H bid. Otherwise, if he was planning to bid 4@S over 4@H, he should bid it right away, before they have a chance to exchange information. If Ira bids 4@S right away, it is much harder for them to double. On the other hand  I think ally's 4@H bid was a bit aggressive. her singleton spade is great, but the rest of her hand is not so good. However once ally bids 4@H, and Ira bids 4@S, pam, you have a very clear double. |
PG| ***** 32 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|You have what looks like 3 sure tricks, plus the K of diamonds, plus ally has some strength. You can't let the opponents steal you blind. As I said before, if you only double when they go down, you are not doubling enough.  My main point in discussing what Ira should bid is, if you are playing against strong opponents and you suspect they have game, either preempt to 4 right away, or don't preempt at all. It turns out, 4@H makes if ally guesses the heart suit, or else is down 1.|
