^-{    BERGEN RAISES    }
^-|CP||fp||at|^-Here is a brief explanation of Bergen Raises by Howard.
^-^B@2^Y@3"Bergen Raises are used by responder after partner opens one of a major and responder has 4 cards in the opener's suit. Reverse Bergen, which I recommend, works as follows. Responder must have exactly 4 card support. The point count specified is "Dummy Points", as defined in Bergen's book Slam Bidding Made Easier.|
PG| ***** 147 ***** |


CP|8|FP|2|AT|

- with 5-6 points, responder jumps to 3 of the major (more on this later), |
PG| ***** 148 ***** |


AT|
- with 7-9 responder bids 3 diamonds (known as a "constructive raise"), |
PG| ***** 149 ***** |


AT|
- with a 10-12 responder bids 3 clubs (known as a "limit raise"), and |
PG| ***** 150 ***** |


AT|
- with 13 or more responder bids 2N or Splinter (the usual Jacoby 2N raise played by many partnerships)."|
PG| ***** 151 ***** |


FP||CP||AT|

"One of the important advantages of Bergen Raises is the preemptive jump raise (with 5-6 points). Modern competitive bidding theory says it is safe to compete to the 3 level with a 9 card fit, and Bergen Raises allow you to do this in a way that preempts the opponents."|
PG| ***** 152 ***** |


FP|2|cs|4|CP|8|AT|^-

{"If the intervening opponent bids, Bergen Raises no longer apply."} 

^-|CP||CS||FP||AT|"I suggest you play the following methods over interference. If the opponent bids a suit, 
- a cue bid shows a limit raise (10-12) with 4 card support. 
- a jump raise shows less than a limit raise (5-8) with 4 card support.

Over a takeout double, 
- 2N shows a limit raise or better with 4 card support (this convention is known as Jordan 2N), and a 
- jump raise still shows less than a limit raise (5-8) with 4 card support." 
|
PG| ***** 153 ***** |


